; font-weight: normal; text-align: left;\" | There have been numerous films based on ''[[Dracula]]'', an 1897 [[Gothic fiction|Gothic horror]] novel by Irish author [[Bram Stoker]]. It introduced the character of [[Count Dracula]], and established many conventions of subsequent [[Vampire literature|vampire fantasy]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bramstoker.org/novels.html|title=Bram Stoker - Novels|website=Bramstoker.org|accessdate=8 October 2017}}</ref> The novel tells the story of Dracula's attempt to move from [[Transylvania]] to England so that he may find new blood and spread the undead curse, and of the battle between Dracula and a small group of men and a woman led by Professor [[Abraham Van Helsing]]. Some filmmakers have also combined fact with fiction and merged Stoker's Dracula with the real [[Vlad the Impaler|Vlad III Dracula]], often called Vlad Tepes and Vlad the Impaler.<br><br>\n! width=\"390\" | Title\n! width=\"70\" | Release date\n! width=\"185\" | Country\n! width=\"250\" | Director\n! width=\"370\" | Leading cast\n! width=\"450\" | Notes\n|-\n| ''[[Drakula (1920 film)|Drakula]]'' (\u0414\u0440\u0430\u043a\u0443\u043b\u0430) \n| 1920 \n| Russia\n|\n|\n| {{small|Nothing regarding this [[silent film]] is known to survive; there are no known production stills, and there is very little information about this film available. Most sources agree that the existence of this film is questionable, because no details appear to have survived, and its existence is not verifiable.<ref>Glut, Donald F. ''The Dracula Book'' (1975) (\"Other film versions of Dracula are reported to have been made about this time \u2014 one being Russian \u2014 but there is no real verification to substantiate these claims.\")</ref>}}\n|-\n| ''[[Dracula's Death]]'' (Drakula hal\u00e1la)\n| 1921.08\n| Hungary\n| [[K\u00e1roly Lajthay]]\n| Erik Vanko, Lena Myl, [[Carl Goetz]]\n| {{small|Unlicensed Hungarian adaptation. First known film appearance of Dracula. This film has been [[Lost 