]], [[Craig Sheffer]]<br>[[Jason Scott Lee]], [[Jason London]], [[Alexandra Wescourt]]\n|| <br>{{small|A modern reworking of the story.<br>First sequel.<br>Second sequel.}}\n|-\n| ''[[The Breed (2001 film)|The Breed]]'' \n| 2001.07.19\n| United States\n| [[Michael Oblowitz]]\n| [[Adrian Paul]], [[Bokeem Woodbine]], [[Bai Ling]]\n| {{small|In a dystopic future in which vampires are a marginalized race living in formerly Jewish ghettos, two officers, one human and the other a vampire, investigate a series of strange murders with the aid of female vampire [[Lucy Westenra]] (played by [[Bai Ling]]).}}\n|-\n| ''[[Dracula, Pages from a Virgin's Diary]]'' \n| 2002.02.28\n| Canada\n| [[Guy Maddin]]\n| Zhang Wei-Qiang, [[Tara Birtwhistle]], David Moroni\n| {{small|A wordless interpretation of the Royal Winnipeg Ballet's take of ''Bram Stoker's Dracula''.}}\n|-\n| ''[[The League of Extraordinary Gentlemen (film)|The League of Extraordinary Gentlemen]]'' \n| 2003.07.11\n| United Kingdom/United States\n| [[Stephen Norrington]]\n| [[Sean Connery]], [[Naseeruddin Shah]], [[Shane West]]\n| {{small|Mina Harker, now a vampire thanks to her encounter with Dracula, is a member of the League.}}\n|-\n| ''[[Van Helsing (film)|Van Helsing]]'' \n| 2004.05.07\n| United States\n| [[Stephen Sommers]]\n| [[Hugh Jackman]], [[Kate Beckinsale]], [[Richard Roxburgh]]\n| {{small|Horror/action-adventure film only loosely connected to the novel ''Dracula''. Van Helsing's appearance is heavily based on the look of [[Vampire Hunter D]], a vampire hunter who is the implied son of Dracula.}}\n|-\n| ''[[Blade: Trinity]]'' \n| 2004.12.08\n| United States\n| [[David S. Goyer]]\n| [[Wesley Snipes]], [[Jessica Biel]], [[Dominic Purcell]]\n| {{small|Drake the vampire is supposed to have had many aliases throughout the centuries, Stoker's Dracula being one of them.}}\n|-\n| ''[[Dracula 3000]]''\n| 2004.12.07\n| United States/South Africa\n| [[Darrell Roodt]]\n| [[Casper Van Dien]], [[Erika Eleniak]], [[Tom Lister Jr.|Tom \"Tiny\" Lister]]\n| {{small|A TV movie that brings Count Dracula into outer space in the distant 30th century.}}\n|-\n| ''[[Bram Stoker's Dracula's Curse]]'' \n| 2006.04.25\n| United States\n| Leigh Scott\n| Thomas Downey, Rhett Giles, Christina Rosenberg\n| {{small|A direct-to-video release from [[The Asylum]].}}\n|-\n| ''[[Dracula (2006 film)|Dracula]]'' \n| 2006.12.28\n| United Kingdom\n| [[Bill Eagles]]\n| [[Marc Warren]], [[David Suchet]], [[Sophia Myles]]\n| {{small|The second [[BBC]] version, with a reworked plot.}}\n|-\n| ''[[Hellsing Ultimate]]'' \n| 2006.02.10\n| Japan\n| [[Tomokazu Tokoro]], Hideki Tonokatsu\n| [[Jouji Nakata]], [[Fumiko Orikasa]], [[Yoshiko Sakakibara]]\n| {{small|A remake of ''Hellsing'', following the original manga series more closely.}}\n|-\n| ''[[Scary or Die]]''\n| 2012.05.01\n| United States\n| {{small|Bob Badway, Michael Emanuel, Igor Meglic}}\n| [[Charles Rahi Chun]], Alexandria Choi, Azion Iemekeve\n| {{small|Horror/comedy/anthology film featuring one vampire segment (\"Taejung's Lament\") with vampire hunter [[Van Helsing]].<ref>https://www.allmovie.com/movie/scary-or-die-v566626</ref>}}\n|-\n| Hotel Transylvania\n\u3000\u3000''[[Hotel Transylvania]]''<br>\n\u3000\u3000''[[Hotel Transylvania 2]]<br>''\n\u3000\u3000''[[Hotel Transylvania 3: Summer Vacation]]''\n|| <br>2012.09.28<br>2015.09.25<br>2018.07.13\n|| <br>United States<br>United States<br>United States\n|| <br>[[Genndy Tartakovsky]]<br>[[Genndy Tartakovsky]]<br>[[Genndy Tartakovsky]]<br>\n|| <br>[[Adam Sandler]], [[Andy Samberg]], [[Selena Gomez]]<br>[[Adam Sandler]], [[Andy Samberg]], [[Selena Gomez]]<br>[[Adam Sandler]], [[Andy Samberg]], [[Selena Gomez]]<br>\n|| <br>{{small|Computer-animated horror/comedy film.<br>First sequel.<br>Second sequel.}}\n|-\n| ''[[Dracula 3D]]'' \n| 2012.05.19\n| Italy/France/Spain\n| [[Thomas Kretschmann]], [[Rutger Hauer]], [[Marta Gastini]], [[Asia Argento]]\n| [[Dario Argento]]\n| {{small|Not a direct adaptation of Bram Stoker's ''Dracula'', but features several elements from the novel.}}\n|-\n| ''[[Saint Dracula 3D]]'' \n| 2012.11.23\n| [[United Arab Emirates]]\n| [[Rupesh Paul]]\n| Mitch Powell,  Patricia Duarte, Daniel Shayler \n| {{small|Independent horror film.}}\n|-\n| ''[[Dracula 2012]]''\n| 2013.02.08\n| India\n| [[Vinayan]]\n| Sudheer Sukumaran, [[Monal Gajjar]], [[Shraddha Das]]\n| {{small|A 3-D horror film.}}\n|-\n|  ''[[Dracula: The Dark Prince]]''\n| 2013.10.15\n| United States\n| [[Pearry Reginald Teo]]\n| [[Luke Roberts (actor)|Luke Roberts]], [[Jon Voight]], [[Kelly Wenham]]\n| {{small|A fantasy horror film shot in [[Romania]].}}\n|-\n| ''[[Dracula Untold]]''\n| 2014.10.10\n| United States\n| [[Gary Shore]]\n| [[Luke Evans (actor)|Luke Evans]], [[Dominic Cooper]], [[Sarah Gadon]], [[Charles Dance]]\n| {{small|Dark fantasy/horror film where Dracula is once again Vlad the Impaler.}}\n|}\n\n== Carmilla films ==\n\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|+ align=\"top\" style=\"caption-side:top; font-weight: normal; text-align: left;\" | There have been numerous films based on ''[[Carmilla]]'', an 1872 [[Gothic fiction|Gothic novel]]la by Irish author [[Sheridan Le Fanu|Joseph Sheridan Le Fanu]] and one of the early works of [[vampire fiction]], predating [[Bram Stoker]]'s ''[[Dracula]]'' (1897) by 26 years. The story is narrated by a young woman preyed upon by a female vampire named Carmilla, later revealed to be Mircalla, Countess Karnstein (Carmilla is an anagram of Mircalla). The character is a prototypical example of the lesbian vampire, expressing romantic desires toward the protagonist.<br><br>\n! width=\"390\" | Title\n! width=\"70\" | Release Date\n! width=\"185\" | Country\n! width=\"250\" | Director\n! width=\"370\" | Leading Cast\n! width=\"450\" | Notes\n|-\n| ''[[Vampyr]]''\n| 1932.05.06\n| Germany/France\n| [[Carl Theodor Dreyer]]\n| [[Nicolas de Gunzburg|Julian West]]\n| {{small|Loose adaptation with all references to lesbian sexuality deleted by the director.<ref>{{Cite book |last=Grant |first=Barry Keith |authorlink= |last2=Sharrett |first2=Christopher |author2-link= |title=Planks of Reason: Essays on the Horror Film |publisher=Scarecrow Press |year=2004 |location= |page=73 |url =https://books.google.com/books?id=QHg7m_ESR54C&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q&f=false |isbn=0-8108-5013-3}}</ref>}}\n|-\n| ''[[Blood and Roses]]'' (Et mourir de plaisir)\n| 1960.09.14\n| France/Italy\n| [[Roger Vadim]]\n| [[Mel Ferrer]], [[Elsa Martinelli]], [[Annette Stroyberg]]\n| {{small|The second screen adaptation and the first film in the [[lesbian vampire]] genre. Filmed in both English and French.}}\n|-\n| ''[[Terror in the Crypt]]'' (La cripta e l'incubo)\n| 1964.05.27\n| Italy/Spain\n| [[Camillo Mastrocinque]]\n| [[Christopher Lee]], [[Adriana Ambesi]], Pier Anna Quaglia\n| {{small|A more-or-less faithful adaptation. Also known as ''Crypt of the Vampire'' in the U.S. and ''Crypt of Horror'' in the U.K..}}\n|-\n| [[Karnstein Trilogy|The Karnstein Trilogy]] \n\u3000\u3000''[[The Vampire Lovers]]''<br> \n\u3000\u3000''[[Lust for a Vampire]]''<br>\n\u3000\u3000''[[Twins of Evil]]''\n|| <br>1970.10.04<br>1971.01.17<br>1971.10.03\n|| <br>United Kingdom<br>United Kingdom<br>United Kingdom\n|| <br>[[Roy Ward Baker]]<br>[[Jimmy Sangster]]<br>[[John Hough (director)|John Hough]]\n|| <br>[[Ingrid Pitt]], [[George Cole (actor)|George Cole]], [[Kate O'Mara]], [[Peter Cushing]]<br>[[Yutte Stensgaard]], Michael Johnson, [[Ralph Bates]]<br>[[Peter Cushing]], [[Mary Collinson]], [[Madeleine Collinson]]\n|| <br>{{small|With this adaptation, [[Hammer Films|Hammer]] set a trend for lesbian erotica in the genre.<br>First sequel.<br>Second sequel.}}\n|-\n| ''[[The Blood Spattered Bride]]'' (La Novia Ensangrentada)\n| 1972.09.30\n| Spain\n| [[Vicente Aranda]]\n| [[Sim\u00f3n Andreu]], [[Maribel Mart\u00edn]], [[Alexandra Bastedo]]\n| {{small|Spanish horror film based on the text. The film has reached [[Cult film|cult status]] for its mixture of horror, vampirism and seduction with lesbian overtones.}}\n|-\n| ''Carmilla''\n| 1980\n| Poland\n| Janusz Kondratiuk\n| [[Izabela Trojanowska]], Monika Stefanowicz\n| {{small|A black-and-white made-for-television movie adaptation from Poland.}}\n|-\n| ''Carmilla''\n| 1989.09.10\n| United States\n| [[Gabrielle Beaumont]]\n| [[Roy Dotrice]], [[Roddy McDowall]], [[Ione Skye]], [[Meg Tilly]]\n| {{small|TV movie adaption for [[Showtime (TV network)|Showtime]]'s ''[[Nightmare Classics]]'' anthology series, relocating the story to an American antebellum Southern plantation.}}\n|-\n| ''[[Vampires vs. Zombies]]'' \n| 2004.04.13\n| United States\n| Vince D'Amato\n| Bonny Giroux, C.S. Munro, Maratama Carlson\n| {{small|An independent horror film loosely based on the novella, but unlike Le Fanu's story, most of the action in the film takes place inside a car.}}\n|-\n| ''[[Lesbian Vampire Killers]]'' \n| 2009.03.16\n| United Kingdom\n| Phil Claydon\n| [[James Corden]], [[Mathew Horne]], [[MyAnna Buring]]\n| {{small|A spoof of the lesbian vampire genre with [[Silvia Colloca]] as Carmilla.}}\n|-\n| ''[[The Unwanted]]''\n| 2014.03.31\n| United States\n| [[Bret Wood]]\n| [[Hannah Fierman]], Christen Orr, [[William Katt]]\n| {{small|Relocates the story to the contemporary Southern United States.}}\n|-\n| ''The Curse of Styria''\n| 2014.08.21\n| United States/Hungary\n| Mauricio Chernovetzky<br>Mark Devendorf\n| [[Eleanor Tomlinson]], [[Stephen Rea]], [[Julia Pietrucha]]\n| {{small|Adaptation of the novel set in the late 1980s. Also known as ''Angels of Darkness''.}}\n|-\n| ''[[The Carmilla Movie]]'' \n| 2017.10.26\n| Canada\n| Spencer Maybee\n| [[Elise Bauman]], [[Natasha Negovanlis]]\n| {{small|Based on the webseries ''[[Carmilla (series)|Carmilla]]''.}}\n|}\n\n== Elizabeth Bathory films ==\n\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|+ align=\"top\" style=\"caption-side:top; font-weight: normal; text-align: left;\" | There have been a number of vampire films based on or inspired by [[Elizabeth Bathory|Countess Elizabeth B\u00e1thory]] (1560-1614), a [[Hungarian people|Hungarian]] noblewoman and reputed serial killer from the [[Nobility in the Kingdom of Hungary|noble family]] of [[B\u00e1thory]], who owned land in the [[Kingdom of Hungary]] (now Hungary, [[Slovakia]] and [[Romania]]). Stories describing her vampire-like tendencies (most famously the tale that she bathed in the blood of virgins to retain her youth) were generally recorded years after her death, and are considered unreliable. Her story quickly became part of national [[folklore]], and her infamy persists to this day. She is often compared to [[Vlad the Impaler]] of [[Wallachia]] (on whom the fictional [[Count Dracula]] is partly based); some insist that she inspired [[Bram Stoker]]'s novel ''[[Dracula]]'' (1897),<ref>{{cite book |last1=Joshi |first1=S. T. |title=Encyclopedia of the Vampire: The Living Dead in Myth, Legend, and Popular Culture |date=2011 |publisher=ABC-CLIO |isbn=9780313378331 |page=6 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=CaqE82YIh4QC&pg=PA6&dq=B\u00e1thory+Stoker%27s+Dracula |accessdate=29 September 2018 }}</ref> though there is no evidence to support this hypothesis.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Stoker |first1=Bram |last2=Eighteen-Bisang |first2=Robert |last3=Miller |first3=Elizabeth |title=Bram Stoker's Notes for Dracula: A Facsimile Edition |date=2008 |publisher=McFarland |isbn=9780786477302 |page=131 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=geFgAQAAQBAJ&pg=PA131&dq=Elizabeth+B\u00e1thory++Stoker |accessdate=29 September 2018 }}</ref> Nicknames and literary [[epithets]] attributed to her include ''The Blood Countess'' and ''Countess Dracula''.<br><br>\n! width=\"390\" | Title\n! width=\"70\" | Release Date\n! width=\"185\" | Country\n! width=\"250\" | Director\n! width=\"370\" | Leading Cast\n! width=\"450\" | Notes\n|-\n| ''[[Countess Dracula]]'' \n| 1971.02.14\n| United Kingdom\n| [[Peter Sasdy]]\n| [[Ingrid Pitt]], [[Nigel Green]], [[Lesley-Anne Down]]\n| {{small|[[Hammer Films|Hammer film]] based on Countess Elizabeth Bathory.}}\n|-\n| ''[[Daughters of Darkness]]''\n| 1971.10.22\n| {{small|Belgium/France/West Germany}}\n| [[Harry K\u00fcmel]]\n| [[Delphine Seyrig]], Danielle Ouimet, [[John Karlen]]\n| {{small|A film featuring Countess Elizabeth Bathory as a vampire.}}\n|-\n| ''The Legend of Blood Castle'' (Ceremonia sangrienta)\n| 1973.10.04\n| Spain/Italy\n| [[Jorge Grau]]\n| [[Lucia Bos\u00e9]], Espartaco Santoni, [[Ewa Aulin]]\n| {{small|The aging Countess Elizabeth Bathory discovers that the blood of a virgin can temporarily restore her youth and great beauty. She falls in love with a dashing young soldier, but is compelled to kill again and again to maintain her attractiveness and to prevent the secret from getting out.}}\n|-\n| ''[[Thirst (1979 film)|Thirst]]''\n| 1979.09.28\n| United States\n| [[Rod Hardy]]\n| [[Chantal Contouri]], [[Max Phipps]], [[David Hemmings]]\n| {{small|Vampire film featuring a female descendant of Countess Elizabeth Bathory.}}\n|-\n| ''[[Mama Dracula]]''\n| 1980.11.19\n| France/Belgium\n| [[Boris Szulzinger]]\n| [[Louise Fletcher]], [[Maria Schneider (actress)|Maria Schneider]], [[Marc-Henri Wajnberg]]\n| {{small|Based on Countess Elizabeth Bathory and her rejuvenation baths consisting of the blood of young virgins.}}\n|- \n| ''Bloodbath''\n| 1999\n| United States\n| Dan Speaker, Kim Turney\n| Susannah Devereux, Dan Speaker, Jennifer Patterson\n| {{small|A very low budget vampire film with Deveraux as Countess Elizabeth Bathory / Elizabeth Bartholomew.}}\n|-\n| ''[[Eternal (film)|Eternal]]'' \n| 2004.09.24\n| Canada\n| {{small|Wilhelm Liebenberg, Federico Sanchez}}\n| [[Sarah Manninen]], [[Caroline N\u00e9ron]], [[Victoria Sanchez (actress)|Victoria Sanchez]]\n| {{small|Sixteenth-century Countess Elizabeth Bathory repeats her crimes in modern-day Montreal.}}\n|-\n| ''Night Fangs''\n| 2005.10.11\n| United States\n| Ricardo Islas\n| Leslie Frank, Cyn Dulay, Ricardo Islas\n| {{small|Two art teachers are obsessed with eternal youth. Somehow, they manage to get Countess Elizabeth Bathory's diary. Soon, they start to practice bloody rituals that end up unleashing Hell on Earth.}}\n|-\n| ''[[Chastity Bites]]'' \n| 2013.06.01\n| United States\n| John V. Knowles\n| [[Allison Scagliotti]], [[Francia Raisa]], Eddy Rioseco\n| {{small|A feminist blogger and reporter for a school newspaper tries to stop Countess Elizabeth B\u00e1thory, who poses as an abstinence counselor in a high school, from killing the school's virgins to stay young and beautiful.}}\n|-\n| ''[[Fright Night 2: New Blood]]''\n| 2013.10.01\n| United States\n| [[Eduardo Rodr\u00edguez (director)|Eduardo Rodr\u00edguez]]\n| [[Will Payne (actor)|Will Payne]], [[Jaime Murray]], [[Sean Power (actor)|Sean Power]]\n| {{small|A [[reimagining]] of the ''[[Fright Night]]'' films with a female character named \"Gerri Dandridge\", alias Countess Elizabeth Bathory.}}\n|}\n\n== Other vampire films ==\n\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! width=\"390\" | Title\n! width=\"70\" | Release Date\n! width=\"185\" | Country\n! width=\"250\" | Director\n! width=\"370\" | Leading Cast\n! width=\"450\" | Notes\n|-\n| ''[[The House of the Devil (1896 film)|The House of the Devil]]'' (Le Manoir du Diable)\n| 1896\n| France\n| [[Georges M\u00e9li\u00e8s]]\n| [[Jehanne D'Alcy]], Jules-Eug\u00e8ne Legris\n| {{small|Arguably the first vampire film.  The \"vampire\" character is perhaps better identified as the devil, but does use the common vampire trope of transformation into a bat. Under four minutes long and in black-and-white.}}\n|-\n| ''[[The Vampire (1913 film)|The Vampire]]'' \n| 1913.10.15\n| United States\n| [[Robert G. Vignola]]\n| [[Alice Hollister]], [[Harry F. Millarde]], [[Marguerite Courtot]]\n| {{small|Also co-written by Vignola.  The earliest known surviving \"[[Femme fatale|vamp]]\" film.}}\n|-\n| ''[[The Devil's Daughter (1915 film)|The Devil's Daughter]]'' \n| 1915.06.16\n| United States\n| [[Frank Powell]]\n| [[Theda Bara]], 