 Curtis]]\n| {{small|A cult of vampires who feed on the sous of psychics terrorize a young girl.}}\n|}\n\n== See also ==\n*[[Vampire films]]\n*[[List of vampire television series]]\n*[[Vampire literature]]\n*[[List of fictional vampires]]\n*''[[Bloodsucking Cinema]]'', a documentary film about vampire films\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* Lists of the best vampire films:\n** [https://web.archive.org/web/20091030031027/http://www.rottentomatoes.com/guides/best_vampire_movies/ 25 Best Reviewed Vampire Movies] at [[Rotten Tomatoes]]\n** [http://www.cinematical.com/2009/08/06/the-best-and-worst-vampire-movies/ The Best and Worst Vampire Movies] at [[Weblogs, Inc.|Cinematical blog]]\n** [http://movies.about.com/od/toppicks/tp/top-vampire-movies.htm Top 10 Vampire Films] (excluding films with Dracula) at [[About.com]]\n** [https://www.bbc.co.uk/cult/vampires/features/films.shtml Top Vampire Films] from ''[[BBC Cult TV|Cult TV]]''\n** [https://web.archive.org/web/20121006120729/http://snarkerati.com/movie-news/top-70-vampire-movies-of-all-time/ Top 70 vampire films] top 70 list of vampire films of all time\n** [http://taliesinttlg.blogspot.com/2009/01/taliesins-top-100.html Taliesin's Top 100] the top 100 on the Taliesin Meets the Vampires blog\n* [http://www.vampyrus.com Vampyrus]\n* [http://www.horrormusic.net Horror Music]\n{{Adaptations of Dracula}}\n[[Category:Lists of horror films|Vampire]]\n[[Category:Vampires in film| ]]\n", "name_user": "TMProofreader", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eDracula films", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_vampire_films"}
{"title_page": "Anastasian War", "text_new": "{{Infobox military conflict\n| conflict    = Anastasian War\n| partof      = the [[Roman-Persian Wars]]\n| image       = [[File:Roman-Persian Frontier in Late Antiquity.svg|250px|The Roman-Persian frontier had remained stable since 384, when the two powers divided Armenia, and despite recurrent warfare, would not change significantly until the Lazic War]]\n| image_size  =\n| alt         =\n| caption     = The Roman-Persian frontier had remained stable since 384, when the two powers divided Armenia, and despite recurrent warfare, would not change significantly until the [[Lazic War]].\n| date        = 502\u2013506 AD\n| place       = [[Osroene]], [[Upper Mesopotamia]], [[Armenia]], [[Southeastern Anatolia Region, Turkey|Southeastern Anatolia]]\n| coordinates = \n| map_type    = \n| map_relief  = \n| map_size    = \n| map_marksize = \n| map_caption = \n| map_label   = \n| territory   = The Sassanian Empire captures [[Erzurum|Theodosiopolis]] and [[Silvan, Diyarbak\u0131r|Martyropolis]]\n| result      = Peace treaty<br>The [[Byzantine Empire]] pays 1,000 pounds of gold to the [[Sassanid Empire]]<ref name=\"IO\">http://www.iranicaonline.org/articles/sasanian-dynasty</ref>\n| combatant1  = [[Byzantine Empire]]<br>Arab allies\n| combatant2  = [[Sasanian Empire]]<br>[[Lakhmids]]\n| commander1  = {{plainlist|\n*[[Anastasius I (emperor)|Anastasius I]]\n*[[Areobindus Dagalaiphus Areobindus|Areobindus]]\n*[[Patricius (consul 500)|Patricius]]\n*[[Hypatius (consul 500)|Hypatius]]\n*[[Apion (family)|Apion]]\n*[[Justin I]]\n*[[Patriciolus]]\n*[[Vitalian (general)|Vitalian]]\n*[[Pharesmanes]]\n*[[Celer (magister officiorum)|Celer]]\n*[[Romanus (dux)|Romanus]]\n*[[Constantine (comes rei militaris)|Constantine]]{{POW}}<ref>The sources are contradictory about the role played by Constantine during the siege of Theodosiopolis. According to [[Zacharias Rhetor]], ({{harvnb|Greatrex|2002|p=63}}) he was taken prisoner, while according to [[Joshua the Stylite]], due a grudge he bore against the emperor Anastasius, he betrayed the Romans.({{harvnb|Martindale|1980|p=314}})</ref>\n*Godidisklus\n*[[Bessas (general)|Bessas]]\n*[[Rufinus (patricius)|Rufinus]]\n*Asouades\n*Bonosus\n*Timostratus\n}}\n| commander2  = {{plainlist|\n*[[Kavadh I]]\n*Theodore\n*[[Al-Mundhir III ibn al-Nu'man]]\n*[[Adergoudounbades]]\n*[[Bawi]]\n*[[Glones]]{{KIA}}\n*Mirranes ([[Perozes]]?)\n}}\n| units1      = \n| units2      = \n| strength1   = \n| strength2   = \n| casualties1 = \n| casualties2 = \n| notes       = \n| campaignbox = {{Campaignbox Roman-Persian Wars}}\n{{Campaignbox Anastasian War}}\n}}\nThe '''Anastasian War''' was fought from 502 to 506 between the [[Byzantine Empire]] and the [[Sasanian Empire]]. It was the first major conflict between the two powers since 440, and would be the prelude to a long [[Byzantine-Sassanid Wars|series of destructive conflicts]] between the two empires over the next century.\n\n==Prelude==\nSeveral factors underlay the termination of the longest period of peace the [[Byzantine Empire|Eastern Roman]] and the [[Sassanid Empire]] ever enjoyed. The Persian king [[Kavadh I]] needed money to pay his debts to the [[Hephthalites]] who had helped him regain his throne in 498/499. The situation was exacerbated by recent changes in the flow of the [[Tigris]] in [[Lower Mesopotamia]], sparking famines and flood. When the Roman emperor [[Anastasius I (emperor)|Anastasius I]] refused to provide any help, Kavadh tried to gain the money by force.<ref>Procopius. ''History of the Wars'', I.7.1-2; {{harvnb|Greatrex|Lieu|2002|p=62}}.</ref>\n\n==War==\n\n[[File:NE 500ad.jpg|thumb|left|175px|Roman and Persian Empires in 500, also showing their neighbors, many of whom were dragged into wars between the great powers.]]\n\n===Kavadh I's campaign of 502===\n\nIn 502, Kavadh quickly captured the unprepared city of [[Theodosiopolis (Armenia)|Theodosiopolis]], perhaps with local support; the city was in any case undefended by troops and weakly fortified.<ref>{{harvnb|Greatrex|Lieu|2002|p=62}}.</ref> [[Martyropolis]] also [[Siege of Martyropolis (502)|fell]] in the same year. Kavadh then besieged the fortress-city of [[Amida (Roman city)|Amida]] through the autumn and winter (502-503) and captured it after a lengthy siege, although the defenders were unsupported by troops.<ref>{{harvnb|Greatrex|Lieu|2002|p=63}}.</ref> Many people, particularly the population of Amida, were [[deportation|deported]] to [[Pars (Sasanian province)|Pars]] and [[Khuzestan]] in Persia, in particular, to the new city of [[Veh-az-Amid Kavad]] (Arrajan).<ref>A. Shapur Shahbazi, Erich Kettenhofen, John R. Perry, \u201cDEPORTATIONS,\u201d ''[[Encyclop\u00e6dia Iranica]]'', VII/3, pp. 297-312, available online at http://www.iranicaonline.org/articles/deportations (accessed on 30 December 2012).</ref>\n\n===Anastasius' campaign of 503 and Kavad I's counterattack===\n\nThe Byzantine emperor [[Anastasius I (emperor)|Anastasius I]] dispatched an army in May 503 against the Sasanians. The army was the largest Roman force in the East since [[Julian's Persian War|Julian's invasion of Persia]]. The force gathered at [[Edessa]] and [[Samosata]]. It operated in three divisions under ''[[magister militum per Orientem]]'' [[Areobindus Dagalaiphus Areobindus|Areobindus]], ''[[strategos]]'' [[Patricius (consul 500)|Patricius]], and [[Hypatius (consul 500)|Hypatius]]. Hypatius and Patricius attacked Amida, which was held by a 3,000-strong garrison under [[Glones]]. Areobindus, together with [[Romanus (dux)|Romanus]] and thee Arab ''[[phylarch]]'' Asouades (Aswad) (probably a [[Kindah]] leader) attacked [[Nisibis]], in which Kavadh I was residing.<ref name=\"Heather\">{{cite book |last1=Heather |first1=Peter J. |title=Rome Resurgent: War and Empire in the Age of Justinian |date=2018 |publisher=Oxford University Press |isbn=978-0-19-936274-5 |page=77 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last1=Shahid |first1=Irfan |title=Byzantium and the Arabs in the Sixth Century |date=1995 |publisher=Dumbarton Oaks |isbn=978-0-88402-214-5 |page=21 |language=en}}</ref> Procopius also mentions [[Celer (magister officiorum)|Celer]] as a fourth commander.<ref name=\"Procopius61\" /> Notable officers associated with this force include ''\"[[hyparch]]\"'' [[Apion (family)|Apion I]] (the Egyptian),<ref>{{cite book |last1=Bury |first1=John Bagnell |title=History of the Later Roman Empire from the Death of Theodosius I. to the Death of Justinian |date=1958 |publisher=Courier Corporation |isbn=978-0-486-20398-0 |page=471 |language=en}}</ref> ''[[comes]]'' [[Justin I|Justin]] (the future emperor),<ref name=\"Dodgeon\" />  [[Patriciolus]] and his son [[Vitalian (general)|Vitalian]] (who later revolted against Anastasius), the Colchian [[Pharesmanes]], and the Goths Godidisklus and [[Bessas (general)|Bessas]].<ref name=\"Procopius62\">{{cite book |author1=Procopius of Caesarea |authorlink1=Procopius of Caesarea |title=History of the Wars: Books 1-2 (Persian War) |date=2007 |publisher=Cosimo, Inc. |isbn=978-1-60206-445-4 |pages=61-63 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=toHxDMLTJ4MC&lpg=PA63&pg=PA63 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nInitially, Areobindus gained the upper hand in Nisibis, but Kavadh I's counterattack defeated him, plundered his fort Apadna, and forced him to retreat westward; Hypatius and Patricius attempted to assist him, but it was too late.<ref name=\"Heather\" /> They failed to join with Areobindus and were decisively defeated between Apadna and [[Tell Beshme]] and retreated to Samosata. According to Zacharias, their cavalry suffered heavily during the retreat, falling from the cliffs of mountains. Kavadh continued westward to [[Constantia (Osrhoene)|Constantia]] but failed to capture it, though received supplies from its inhabitants. In early September, Kacadh reached near Edessa. Areobindus rejected Kavadh I's demand of {{convert|10,000|lb}} of gold in exchange for peace. Sasanians and [[Lakhmids]]s overran much of Osrhoene but attempts to attack the fortified city failed. Meanwhile, Byzantine forces under [[Pharesmanes]] attacked Amida, who killed the Sasanian commander [[Glones]] through cunning. This, together with Hunnic incursions, the arrival of Byzantine reinforcements, and Kavadh I's lack of supplies, all forced him to withdraw to Persia. This further contributed to the reputation of Edessa as being impregnable.<ref name=\"Dodgeon\">{{cite book |last1=Dodgeon |first1=Michael H. |last2=Lieu |first2=Samuel N. C. |title=The Roman Eastern Frontier and the Persian Wars Ad 363-628 |date=1991 |publisher=Psychology Press |isbn=978-0-415-46530-4 |pages=68-72 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{harvnb|Greatrex|Lieu|2002|pp=69\u201371}}.</ref> Meanwhile, the ''dux'' of Osrhoene, Timostratus, defeated the Lakhmids, and the [[Tha'labites]] (Byzantine Arabs) attacked Lakhmid capital [[al-Hira]].<ref name=\"Dodgeon\" />\n\n===Anastasius' renewed assault===\n\nIn the summer of 503, Anastasius sent reinforcements under ''[[magister officiorum]]'' [[Celer (magister officiorum)|Celer]] and canceled taxes from Mesopotamia and Osrhoene, while Hypatius and Apion were recalled. Patricius moved to Amida, defeated a force sent against him, and invested the city; Celer joined him later in the spring of 504. While the siege was ongoing, Celer raided [[Beth Arabaye]], while Areobindus raided [[Arzanene]]. Sasanian weakness at this point is apparent by defections to the Byzantine side by the renegade Constantine, a certain Arab chief Adid, and the Armenian Mushlek. The Byzantines eventually captured Amida.<ref name=\"Greatrex-Lieu (2002), 77\" /><ref name=\"Dodgeon\" />\n\n===Peace treaty===\n\nIn the same year, an armistice was agreed as a result of an invasion of Armenia by the [[Hun]]s from the Caucasus. Negotiations between the two powers took place, but such was the distrust that in 506 the Romans, suspecting treachery, seized the Persian officials; once released, the Persians preferred to stay in [[Nisibis]].<ref name=\"Greatrex-Lieu (2002), 77\">{{harvnb|Greatrex|Lieu|2002|p=77}}.</ref> In November 506, a treaty was finally agreed, but little is known of what the terms of the treaty were. [[Procopius]] states that peace was agreed for seven years, and it is likely that some payments were made to the Persians.<ref>Procopius. ''History of the Wars'', I.9.24; {{harvnb|Greatrex|Lieu|2002|p=77}}.</ref> The Persians did not keep Byzantine territory and no annual tribute was paid so it seems the peace treaty was not harsh on the Byzantines.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|title=Rome resurgent : war and empire in the age of Justinian|last=Heather, P. J. (Peter J.)|publisher=Oxford University Press|year=2018|isbn=9780199362745|location=New York, NY|pages=|oclc=1007044617}}</ref>\n\n==Aftermath==\nThe Roman generals blamed many of their difficulties in this war on their lack of a major base in the immediate vicinity of the frontier, a role filled for the Persians by Nisibis (which until its secession in 363 had served the same purpose for the Romans), and in 505 Anastasius therefore ordered the building of a great fortified city at [[Dara (Mesopotamia)|Dara]]. The dilapidated fortifications were also upgraded at Edessa, [[Batnae]] and Amida.<ref>{{harvnb|Greatrex|Lieu|2002|p=74}}.</ref>\n\nAlthough no further large-scale conflict took place during Anastasius's reign, tensions continued, especially while work continued at Dara. This construction project was to become a key component of the Roman defenses, and also a lasting source of controversy with the Persians, who complained that its construction violated the treaty agreed in 422, by which both empires had agreed not to establish new fortifications in the frontier zone. Anastasius, however, pursued the project, deflecting Kavadh's complaints with money.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/belisariuslastro00ianh|title=Belisarius : the last Roman general|last=Hughes, Ian (Historian)|date=2009|publisher=Westholme|isbn=9781594160851|location=Yardley, Pa.|oclc=294885267|url-access=registration}}</ref> The Persians were in any case unable to stop the work, and the walls were completed by 507/508.<ref name=\"Greatrex-Lieu (2002), 77\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==Sources==\n\n===Primary===\n{{refbegin}}\n*{{cite book|last1=Procopius|last2=Dewing|first2=H. B. (trans.)|title=History of the Wars|url=https://archive.org/details/b24750281_0001}} [http://www.gutenberg.org/files/16764/16764-8.txt Books I\u2013II].\n{{refend}}\n\n===Secondary===\n{{refbegin}}\n*{{cite book|last=Greatrex|first=Geoffrey|last2=Lieu|first2=Samuel N. C.|title=The Roman Eastern Frontier and the Persian Wars (Part II, 363\u2013630 AD)|location=New York, New York and London, United Kingdom|publisher=Routledge (Taylor & Francis)|year=2002|isbn=0-415-14687-9|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=zc8iAQAAIAAJ|ref=harv}}\n{{refend}}\n\n[[Category:500s in the Byzantine Empire]]\n[[Category:6th century in Iran]]\n[[Category:500s conflicts]]\n[[Category:Roman\u2013Sasanian Wars]]\n[[Category:6th century in Asia]]\n[[Category:500s]]\n[[Category:502]]\n[[Category:506]]\n[[Category:Anastasian War| ]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox military conflict\n| conflict    = Anastasian War\n| partof      = the [[Roman-Persian Wars]]\n| image       = [[File:Roman-Persian Frontier in Late Antiquity.svg|250px|The Roman-Persian frontier had remained stable since 384, when the two powers divided Armenia, and despite recurrent warfare, would not change significantly until the Lazic War]]\n| image_size  =\n| alt         =\n| caption     = The Roman-Persian frontier had remained stable since 384, when the two powers divided Armenia, and despite recurrent warfare, would not change significantly until the [[Lazic War]].\n| date        = 502\u2013506 AD\n| place       = [[Osroene]], [[Upper Mesopotamia]], [[Armenia]], [[Southeastern Anatolia Region, Turkey|Southeastern Anatolia]]\n| coordinates = \n| map_type    = \n| map_relief  = \n| map_size    = \n| map_marksize = \n| map_caption = \n| map_label   = \n| territory   = The Sassanian Empire captures [[Erzurum|Theodosiopolis]] and [[Silvan, Diyarbak\u0131r|Martyropolis]]\n| result      = Peace treaty<br>The [[Byzantine Empire]] pays 1,000 pounds of gold to the [[Sassanid Empire]]<ref name=\"IO\">http://www.iranicaonline.org/articles/sasanian-dynasty</ref>\n| combatant1  = [[Byzantine Empire]]<br>Arab allies\n| combatant2  = [[Sasanian Empire]]<br>[[Lakhmids]]\n| commander1  = {{plainlist|\n*[[Anastasius I (emperor)|Anastasius I]]\n*[[Areobindus Dagalaiphus Areobindus|Areobindus]]\n*[[Patricius (consul 500)|Patricius]]\n*[[Hypatius (consul 500)|Hypatius]]\n*[[Apion (family)|Apion]]\n*[[Justin I]]\n*[[Patriciolus]]\n*[[Vitalian (general)|Vitalian]]\n*[[Pharesmanes]]\n*[[Celer (magister officiorum)|Celer]]\n*[[Romanus (dux)|Romanus]]\n*[[Constantine (comes rei militaris)|Constantine]]{{POW}}<ref>The sources are contradictory about the role played by Constantine during the siege of Theodosiopolis. According to [[Zacharias Rhetor]], ({{harvnb|Greatrex|2002|p=63}}) he was taken prisoner, while according to [[Joshua the Stylite]], due a grudge he bore against the emperor Anastasius, he betrayed the Romans.({{harvnb|Martindale|1980|p=314}})</ref>\n*Godidisklus\n*[[Bessas (general)|Bessas]]\n*[[Rufinus (patricius)|Rufinus]]\n*Asouades\n*Bonosus\n*Timostratus\n}}\n| commander2  = {{plainlist|\n*[[Kavadh I]]\n*Theodore\n*[[Al-Mundhir III ibn al-Nu'man]]\n*[[Adergoudounbades]]\n*[[Bawi]]\n*[[Glones]]{{KIA}}\n*Mirranes ([[Perozes]]?)\n}}\n| units1      = \n| units2      = \n| strength1   = \n| strength2   = \n| casualties1 = \n| casualties2 = \n| notes       = \n| campaignbox = {{Campaignbox Roman-Persian Wars}}\n{{Campaignbox Anastasian War}}\n}}\nThe '''Anastasian War''' was fought from 502 to 506 between the [[Byzantine Empire]] and the [[Sasanian Empire]]. It was the first major conflict between the two powers since 440, and would be the prelude to a long [[Byzantine-Sassanid Wars|series of destructive conflicts]] between the two empires over the next century.\n\n==Prelude==\nSeveral factors underlay the termination of the longest period of peace the [[Byzantine Empire|Eastern Roman]] and the [[Sassanid Empire]] ever enjoyed. The Persian king [[Kavadh I]] needed money to pay his debts to the [[Hephthalites]] who had helped him regain his throne in 498/499. The situation was exacerbated by recent changes in the flow of the [[Tigris]] in [[Lower Mesopotamia]], sparking famines and flood. When the Roman emperor [[Anastasius I (emperor)|Anastasius I]] refused to provide any help, Kavadh tried to gain the money by force.<ref>Procopius. ''History of the Wars'', I.7.1-2; {{harvnb|Greatrex|Lieu|2002|p=62}}.</ref>\n\n==War==\n\n[[File:NE 500ad.jpg|thumb|left|175px|Roman and Persian Empires in 500, also showing their neighbors, many of whom were dragged into wars between the great powers.]]\n\n===Kavadh I's campaign of 502===\n\nIn 502, Kavadh quickly captured the unprepared city of [[Theodosiopolis (Armenia)|Theodosiopolis]], perhaps with local support; the city was in any case undefended by troops and weakly fortified.<ref>{{harvnb|Greatrex|Lieu|2002|p=62}}.</ref> [[Martyropolis]] also [[Siege of Martyropolis (502)|fell]] in the same year. Kavadh then besieged the fortress-city of [[Amida (Roman city)|Amida]] through the autumn and winter (502-503) and captured it after a lengthy siege, although the defenders were unsupported by troops.<ref>{{harvnb|Greatrex|Lieu|2002|p=63}}.</ref> Many people, particularly the population of Amida, were [[deportation|deported]] to [[Pars (Sasanian province)|Pars]] and [[Khuzestan]] in Persia, in particular, to the new city of [[Veh-az-Amid Kavad]] (Arrajan).<ref>A. Shapur Shahbazi, Erich Kettenhofen, John R. Perry, \u201cDEPORTATIONS,\u201d ''[[Encyclop\u00e6dia Iranica]]'', VII/3, pp. 297-312, available online at http://www.iranicaonline.org/articles/deportations (accessed on 30 December 2012).</ref>\n\n===Anastasius' campaign of 503 and Kavad I's counterattack===\n\nThe Byzantine emperor [[Anastasius I (emperor)|Anastasius I]] dispatched an army in May 503 against the Sasanians. The army was the largest Roman force in the East since [[Julian's Persian War|Julian's invasion of Persia]]. The force gathered at [[Edessa]] and [[Samosata]]. It operated in three divisions under ''[[magister militum per Orientem]]'' [[Areobindus Dagalaiphus Areobindus|Areobindus]], ''[[strategos]]'' [[Patricius (consul 500)|Patricius]], and [[Hypatius (consul 500)|Hypatius]]. Hypatius and Patricius attacked Amida, which was held by a 3,000-strong garrison under [[Glones]]. Areobindus, together with [[Romanus (dux)|Romanus]] and thee Arab ''[[phylarch]]'' Asouades (Aswad) (probably a [[Kindah]] leader) attacked [[Nisibis]], in which Kavadh I was residing.<ref name=\"Heather\">{{cite book |last1=Heather |first1=Peter J. |title=Rome Resurgent: War and Empire in the Age of Justinian |date=2018 |publisher=Oxford University Press |isbn=978-0-19-936274-5 |page=77 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last1=Shahid |first1=Irfan |title=Byzantium and the Arabs in the Sixth Century |date=1995 |publisher=Dumbarton Oaks |isbn=978-0-88402-214-5 |page=21 |language=en}}</ref> Procopius also mentions [[Celer (magister officiorum)|Celer]] as a fourth commander.<ref name=\"Procopius62\" /> Notable officers associated with this force include ''\"[[hyparch]]\"'' [[Apion (family)|Apion I]] (the Egyptian),<ref>{{cite book |last1=Bury |first1=John Bagnell |title=History of the Later Roman Empire from the Death of Theodosius I. to the Death of Justinian |date=1958 |publisher=Courier Corporation |isbn=978-0-486-20398-0 |page=471 |language=en}}</ref> ''[[comes]]'' [[Justin I|Justin]] (the future emperor),<ref name=\"Dodgeon\" />  [[Patriciolus]] and his son [[Vitalian (general)|Vitalian]] (who later revolted against Anastasius), the Colchian [[Pharesmanes]], and the Goths Godidisklus and [[Bessas (general)|Bessas]].<ref name=\"Procopius62\">{{cite book |author1=Procopius of Caesarea |authorlink1=Procopius of Caesarea |title=History of the Wars: Books 1-2 (Persian War) |date=2007 |publisher=Cosimo, Inc. |isbn=978-1-60206-445-4 |pages=62-63 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=toHxDMLTJ4MC&lpg=PA63&pg=PA63 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nInitially, Areobindus gained the upper hand in Nisibis, but Kavadh I's counterattack defeated him, plundered his fort Apadna, and forced him to retreat westward; Hypatius and Patricius attempted to assist him, but it was too late.<ref name=\"Heather\" /> They failed to join with Areobindus and were decisively defeated between Apadna and [[Tell Beshme]] and retreated to Samosata. According to Zacharias, their cavalry suffered heavily during the retreat, falling from the cliffs of mountains. Kavadh continued westward to [[Constantia (Osrhoene)|Constantia]] but failed to capture it, though received supplies from its inhabitants. In early September, Kacadh reached near Edessa. Areobindus rejected Kavadh I's demand of {{convert|10,000|lb}} of gold in exchange for peace. Sasanians and [[Lakhmids]]s overran much of Osrhoene but attempts to attack the fortified city failed. Meanwhile, Byzantine forces under [[Pharesmanes]] attacked Amida, who killed the Sasanian commander [[Glones]] through cunning. This, together with Hunnic incursions, the arrival of Byzantine reinforcements, and Kavadh I's lack of supplies, all forced him to withdraw to Persia. This further contributed to the reputation of Edessa as being impregnable.<ref name=\"Dodgeon\">{{cite book |last1=Dodgeon |first1=Michael H. |last2=Lieu |first2=Samuel N. C. |title=The Roman Eastern Frontier and the Persian Wars Ad 363-628 |date=1991 |publisher=Psychology Press |isbn=978-0-415-46530-4 |pages=68-72 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{harvnb|Greatrex|Lieu|2002|pp=69\u201371}}.</ref> Meanwhile, the ''dux'' of Osrhoene, Timostratus, defeated the Lakhmids, and the [[Tha'labites]] (Byzantine Arabs) attacked Lakhmid capital [[al-Hira]].<ref name=\"Dodgeon\" />\n\n===Anastasius' renewed assault===\n\nIn the summer of 503, Anastasius sent reinforcements under ''[[magister officiorum]]'' [[Celer (magister officiorum)|Celer]] and canceled taxes from Mesopotamia and Osrhoene, while Hypatius and Apion were recalled. Patricius moved to Amida, defeated a force sent against him, and invested the city; Celer joined him later in the spring of 504. While the siege was ongoing, Celer raided [[Beth Arabaye]], while Areobindus raided [[Arzanene]]. Sasanian weakness at this point is apparent by defections to the Byzantine side by the renegade Constantine, a certain Arab chief Adid, and the Armenian Mushlek. The Byzantines eventually captured Amida.<ref name=\"Greatrex-Lieu (2002), 77\" /><ref name=\"Dodgeon\" />\n\n===Peace treaty===\n\nIn the same year, an armistice was agreed as a result of an invasion of Armenia by the [[Hun]]s from the Caucasus. Negotiations between the two powers took place, but such was the distrust that in 506 the Romans, suspecting treachery, seized the Persian officials; once released, the Persians preferred to stay in [[Nisibis]].<ref name=\"Greatrex-Lieu (2002), 77\">{{harvnb|Greatrex|Lieu|2002|p=77}}.</ref> In November 506, a treaty was finally agreed, but little is known of what the terms of the treaty were. [[Procopius]] states that peace was agreed for seven years, and it is likely that some payments were made to the Persians.<ref>Procopius. ''History of the Wars'', I.9.24; {{harvnb|Greatrex|Lieu|2002|p=77}}.</ref> The Persians did not keep Byzantine territory and no annual tribute was paid so it seems the peace treaty was not harsh on the Byzantines.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|title=Rome resurgent : war and empire in the age of Justinian|last=Heather, P. J. (Peter J.)|publisher=Oxford University Press|year=2018|isbn=9780199362745|location=New York, NY|pages=|oclc=1007044617}}</ref>\n\n==Aftermath==\nThe Roman generals blamed many of their difficulties in this war on their lack of a major base in the immediate vicinity of the frontier, a role filled for the Persians by Nisibis (which until its secession in 363 had served the same purpose for the Romans), and in 505 Anastasius therefore ordered the building of a great fortified city at [[Dara (Mesopotamia)|Dara]]. The dilapidated fortifications were also upgraded at Edessa, [[Batnae]] and Amida.<ref>{{harvnb|Greatrex|Lieu|2002|p=74}}.</ref>\n\nAlthough no further large-scale conflict took place during Anastasius's reign, tensions continued, especially while work continued at Dara. This construction project was to become a key component of the Roman defenses, and also a lasting source of controversy with the Persians, who complained that its construction violated the treaty agreed in 422, by which both empires had agreed not to establish new fortifications in the frontier zone. Anastasius, however, pursued the project, deflecting Kavadh's complaints with money.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/belisariuslastro00ianh|title=Belisarius : the last Roman general|last=Hughes, Ian (Historian)|date=2009|publisher=Westholme|isbn=9781594160851|location=Yardley, Pa.|oclc=294885267|url-access=registration}}</ref> The Persians were in any case unable to stop the work, and the walls were completed by 507/508.<ref name=\"Greatrex-Lieu (2002), 77\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==Sources==\n\n===Primary===\n{{refbegin}}\n*{{cite book|last1=Procopius|last2=Dewing|first2=H. B. (trans.)|title=History of the Wars|url=https://archive.org/details/b24750281_0001}} [http://www.gutenberg.org/files/16764/16764-8.txt Books I\u2013II].\n{{refend}}\n\n===Secondary===\n{{refbegin}}\n*{{cite book|last=Greatrex|first=Geoffrey|last2=Lieu|first2=Samuel N. C.|title=The Roman Eastern Frontier and the Persian Wars (Part II, 363\u2013630 AD)|location=New York, New York and London, United Kingdom|publisher=Routledge (Taylor & Francis)|year=2002|isbn=0-415-14687-9|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=zc8iAQAAIAAJ|ref=harv}}\n{{refend}}\n\n[[Category:500s in the Byzantine Empire]]\n[[Category:6th century in Iran]]\n[[Category:500s conflicts]]\n[[Category:Roman\u2013Sasanian Wars]]\n[[Category:6th century in Asia]]\n[[Category:500s]]\n[[Category:502]]\n[[Category:506]]\n[[Category:Anastasian War| ]]\n", "name_user": "ZxxZxxZ", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eAnastasius' campaign of 503 and Kavad I's counterattack", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Anastasian_War"}
{"title_page": "Motets by Johann Sebastian Bach, discography", "text_new": "This article includes a list of commercial recordings of the [[Motet (Bach)|motets]] of [[Johann Sebastian Bach]]. Bach motets have often been recorded as a set (typically comprising the six motets catalogued as BWV{{nbsp}}225-230).{{efn|\"BWV\" is [[Bach-Werke-Verzeichnis]], a thematic catalogue of Bach's works.}}  However, other motets are attributed to Bach and there is some doubt about the authorship of [[Lobet den Herrn, alle Heiden, BWV 230|''Lobet den Herrn, alle Heiden'', BWV 230]], one of the {{abbr|BWV|Bach-Werke-Verzeichnis (catalogue of Bach's works)}} \"six\".\n\nA single CD can contain the set of six motets plus other works. For example, [[Maasaki Suzuki]]'s 2009 recording on [[BIS Records|BIS]] includes [[O Jesu Christ, meins Lebens Licht, BWV 118|''O Jesu Christ, meins Lebens Licht'', BWV 118]] (which at one time was categorised as a cantata) and [[Ich lasse dich nicht, BWV Anh. 159|''Ich lasse dich nicht'', BWV Anh. 159]] (the authorship of which has been disputed).<ref name=\"BIS\">{{Cite web |url=https://bis.se/conductors/suzuki-masaaki/bach-motets |title=Bach Motets |website=bis.se (BIS Records) |access-date=6 April 2020}}</ref> The motets chosen for a particular recording can reflect the way the balance of opinion changes regarding the status of a particular work. This appears to be the case with the two sets by [[John Eliot Gardiner]] conducting the [[Monteverdi Choir]]. They recorded Bach's motets without {{nowrap|BWV Anh. 159}} in 1980, but included it in their 2011 live recording.<ref name=\"muzie\">[https://www.muziekweb.nl/en/Link/DBX11558 ''Bach: Motets''] and [https://www.muziekweb.nl/en/Link/DBX10438 ''Bach Motets''] at {{url|www.muziekweb.nl}}.</ref>\n\n== Types of choirs ==\nChoirs with [[one voice per part]] (OVPP) are used in some [[historically informed performance]]s of Bach. However, OVPP recordings of the motets are relatively rare. Exceptions include the [[Hilliard Ensemble]]'s second set,<ref name=\"Guardian\">{{Cite news |last=Clements |first=Andrew |url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2007/may/18/classicalmusicandopera.shopping2 |title=Bach: Motets |date=18 May 2007 |work=The Guardian}}</ref> and [[Konrad Jungh\u00e4nel]] with the group Cantus C\u00f6lln.<ref name=\"Bach Cantatas6\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.bach-cantatas.com/Vocal/BWV225-231-Rec6.htm |title= Motets / Recordings \u2013 Part 6 |website=Bach Cantatas Website}}</ref>\n\nAt least some of the motets would have been first performed by singers from Leipzig's [[Thomanerchor]], which comprises boys and young men. This choir has recorded the motets (initially under [[G\u00fcnther Ramin]] in the 1950s),<ref name=\"Bach Cantatas2\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.bach-cantatas.com/Vocal/BWV225-231-Rec2.htm  |title= Motets / Recordings \u2013 Part 2 |website=Bach Cantatas Website}}</ref> as have other choirs with boys' voices such as the [[Choir of New College, Oxford]].<ref name=\"BachCantatas7\"/>\n\n== Instrumental accompaniment ==\nMusic directors need to make choices about the instrumental accompaniment, if any, to be used. There are three possible approaches: \n*instruments doubling the vocal lines, something which is described as playing ''[[colla parte]]'' \n*''[[a cappella]]'', that is, without an accompaniment\n*Some support for the singers from instruments such as an [[Organ (music)|organ]]\n\nSurviving sources do not make it clear what Bach's approach was to the accompaniment of most of these pieces. In the case of [[Der Geist hilft unser Schwachheit auf, BWV 226|''Der Geist hilft unser Schwachheit auf'', BWV 226]] orchestral parts are extant, indicating that choir I was doubled by strings and choir II by reeds (two [[oboe]]s, [[Taille (instrument)|taille]] and [[bassoon]]). There is also a [[basso continuo]] (separate [[violone]] and organ parts are provided) which underlies both choirs.<ref name=\"bachchoir\">{{Cite web |url=https://bach.org/education/motet-bwv-226/ |title=Motet BWV 226 |website=Bach Choir of Bethlehem |access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref>\nAn accompaniment is also specified for ''Lobet den Herrn''.<ref name=\"Leavis\">{{cite web | url= https://www.jstor.org/stable/731829| title=Bach's Setting of Psalm CXVII (BWV.230) | publisher=OUP | work=[[Music & Letters]]. Vol. 52, No. 1 | date=January 1971 | author=Leavis, Ralph}}  Accessed via JSTOR (subscription required)</ref>\n\n[[La Petite Bande]], for example, uses the orchestration of ''Der Geist hilft unser Schwachheit auf'' for the other pieces for double choir.\nHowever, ''a capella'' performance is long-established tradition,<ref name=\"MT\">Emery, W. (1974). Bach in Practice. [[The Musical Times]], 115(1578), 661-661. doi:10.2307/960490. Accessed via JSTOR (subscription required)</ref> which is also reflected in recordings. The Hilliard Ensemble's OVPP version is mainly ''a capella''. They omit the instrumental parts of ''Der Geist hilft unser Schwachheit auf'', but sing ''Lobet den Herrn'' to organ accompaniment.<ref name=\"Guardian\"/>\n\n== History ==\nThe first of the motets to be recorded was [[Jesu, meine Freude, BWV 227|''Jesu meine Freude'']] in 1927. This version was sung in English.<ref name=\"Bach Cantatas1\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.bach-cantatas.com/Vocal/BWV225-231-Rec1.htm|title= Motets / Recordings \u2013 Part 1 |website=Bach Cantatas Website}}</ref>\n\n== Awards ==\nIn 2010, Suzuki and his ensemble were given a French award ([[Diapason d'Or|Diapason d\u2019Or de l\u2019Ann\u00e9e]]) and a German award ([[Preis der deutschen Schallplattenkritik]]) for their recording of Bach motets on BIS.\n \nJohn Eliot Gardiner, who has won more [[Gramophone Classical Music Awards|Gramophone Awards]] than any other living artist, received one for his second recording of the motets with the Monteverdi Choir on SDG. It was one of the [[Gramophone_Classical_Music_Awards#2013|2013 awards]], the category being \"Baroque Vocal\".\n\nGrete Pedersen with the Norwegian choir [[Det Norske Solistkor]] won a Diapason d'Or in 2018 for their recording of the motets on BIS.\n\n== Discography ==\nThe intention has been to feature versions which are still available. The year given is that of recording. In the case of pre-1980s recordings, the date of reissue on CD can be significantly later than the original recording.\n{{Cantata discography header |work= Bach Motets |show_more=yes |more = Additional info}}\n{{Cantata discography row\n| id = Ramin\n| title = 6 Motetten<ref name=\"Bach Cantatas2\"/>\n| conductor = {{sortname|G\u00fcnther|Ramin}}\n| choir = [[Thomanerchor]]\n| instrumentalists =\n| soloists = {{plainlist|\n}}\n| label = [[Archiv]] (reissue)\n| year = 1950s\n| more =\n}}\n{{Cantata discography row\n| id = Christophers\n| title = The Six Motets<ref name=\"BachCantatas5\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.bach-cantatas.com/Vocal/BWV225-231-Rec5.htm|title= Motets / Recordings \u2013 Part 5 |website=Bach Cantatas Website}}</ref>\n| conductor = {{sortname|Harry|Christophers}}\n| choir = [[The Sixteen]]\n| instrumentalists =\n| soloists = {{plainlist|\n}}\n| label = [[Hyperion Records|Hyperion]]\n| year = 1989\n| more =\n}}\n{{Cantata discography row\n| id = \n| title = Bach Motetten\n| conductor = \n| choir = [[Hilliard Ensemble]]\n| instrumentalists =\n| soloists = {{plainlist|\n}}\n| label = [[ECM Records|ECM]]\n| year = 2003\n| more = second Hilliard recording\n}}\n{{Cantata discography row\n| id = Higginbottom\n| title = Bach Motets<ref name=\"BachCantatas7\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.bach-cantatas.com/Vocal/BWV225-231-Rec7.htm|title= Motets / Recordings \u2013 Part 7 |website=Bach Cantatas Website}}</ref>\n| conductor = [[Edward Higginbottom]]\n| choir = [[Choir of New College, Oxford]]\n| instrumentalists = organ\n| soloists = {{plainlist|\n}}\n| label = Novum<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.newcollegechoir.com/news/?pid=7&nid=1&storyid=12 |title=Recordings |website=Choir of New College, Oxford}}</ref>\n| year = 2008\n| more = organ accompaniment\n}}\n{{Cantata discography row\n| id = Suzuki\n| title = Bach Motets<ref name=\"BIS\"></ref>\n| conductor = {{sortname|Masaaki|Suzuki}}\n| choir = [[Bach Collegium Japan]]\n| instrumentalists =\n| soloists = {{plainlist|\n}}\n| label = [[BIS Records|BIS]]\n| year = 2009\n| more =\n}}\n{{Cantata discography row\n| id = Gardiner2\n| title =Bach Motets<ref name=\"muzie\"></ref>\n| conductor = {{sortname|John Eliot|Gardiner}}\n| choir = [[Monteverdi Choir]]\n| instrumentalists =\n| soloists = {{plainlist|\n}}\n| label = [[Soli Deo Gloria (record label)|SDG]]\n| year = 2011\n| more = second Gardiner recording\n}}\n{{Cantata discography row\n| id = Pedersen\n| title =\n| conductor = {{sortname|Grete|Pedersen}}\n| choir = [[Det Norske Solistkor|Norwegian Soloists' Choir]]\n| instrumentalists = Ensemble Allegria\n| soloists = {{plainlist|\n}}\n| label = BIS\n| year = 2017\n| more = \n}}\n{{End}}\n{{expand list|date=April 2020}}\n\n== Notes ==\n{{notelist}}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Discographies of compositions by J. S. Bach]]\n", "text_old": "This article includes a list of commercial recordings of the [[Motet (Bach)|motets]] of [[Johann Sebastian Bach]]. Bach motets have often been recorded as a set (typically comprising the six motets catalogued as BWV{{nbsp}}225-230).{{efn|\"BWV\" is [[Bach-Werke-Verzeichnis]], a thematic catalogue of Bach's works.}}  However, other motets are attributed to Bach and there is some doubt about the authorship of [[Lobet den Herrn, alle Heiden, BWV 230|''Lobet den Herrn, alle Heiden'', BWV 230]], one of the {{abbr|BWV|Bach-Werke-Verzeichnis (catalogue of Bach's works)}} \"six\".\n\nA single CD can contain the set of six motets plus other works. For example, [[Maasaki Suzuki]]'s 2009 recording on [[BIS Records|BIS]] includes [[O Jesu Christ, meins Lebens Licht, BWV 118|''O Jesu Christ, meins Lebens Licht'', BWV 118]] (which at one time was categorised as a cantata) and [[Ich lasse dich nicht, BWV Anh. 159|''Ich lasse dich nicht'', BWV Anh. 159]] (the authorship of which has been disputed).<ref name=\"BIS\">{{Cite web |url=https://bis.se/conductors/suzuki-masaaki/bach-motets |title=Bach Motets |website=bis.se (BIS Records) |access-date=6 April 2020}}</ref> The motets chosen for a particular recording can reflect the way the balance of opinion changes regarding the status of a particular work. This appears to be the case with the two sets by [[John Eliot Gardiner]] conducting the [[Monteverdi Choir]]. They recorded Bach's motets without {{nowrap|BWV Anh. 159}} in 1980, but included it in their 2011 live recording.<ref name=\"muzie\">[https://www.muziekweb.nl/en/Link/DBX11558 ''Bach: Motets''] and [https://www.muziekweb.nl/en/Link/DBX10438 ''Bach Motets''] at {{url|www.muziekweb.nl}}.</ref>\n\n== Types of choirs ==\nChoirs with [[one voice per part]] (OVPP) are used in some [[historically informed performance]]s of Bach. However, OVPP recordings of the motets are relatively rare. Exceptions include the [[Hilliard Ensemble]]'s second set,<ref name=\"Guardian\">{{Cite news |last=Clements |first=Andrew |url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2007/may/18/classicalmusicandopera.shopping2 |title=Bach: Motets |date=18 May 2007 |work=The Guardian}}</ref> and [[Konrad Jungh\u00e4nel]] with the group Cantus C\u00f6lln.<ref name=\"Bach Cantatas6\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.bach-cantatas.com/Vocal/BWV225-231-Rec6.htm |title= Motets / Recordings \u2013 Part 6 |website=Bach Cantatas Website}}</ref>\n\nAt least some of the motets would have been first performed by singers from Leipzig's [[Thomanerchor]], which comprises boys and young men. This choir has recorded the motets (initially under [[G\u00fcnther Ramin]] in the 1950s),<ref name=\"Bach Cantatas2\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.bach-cantatas.com/Vocal/BWV225-231-Rec2.htm  |title= Motets / Recordings \u2013 Part 2 |website=Bach Cantatas Website}}</ref> as have other choirs with boys' voices such as the [[Choir of New College, Oxford]].<ref name=\"BachCantatas7\"/>\n\n== Instrumental accompaniment ==\nMusic directors need to make choices about the instrumental accompaniment, if any, to be used. There are three possible approaches: \n*instruments doubling the vocal lines, something which is described as playing ''[[colla parte]]'' \n*''[[a cappella]]'', that is, without an accompaniment: a tradition of performing the motets \n*Some support for the singers from instruments such as an [[Organ (music)|organ]]\n\nSurviving sources do not make it clear what Bach's approach was to the accompaniment of most of these pieces. In the case of [[Der Geist hilft unser Schwachheit auf, BWV 226|''Der Geist hilft unser Schwachheit auf'', BWV 226]] orchestral parts are extant, indicating that choir I was doubled by strings and choir II by reeds (two [[oboe]]s, [[Taille (instrument)|taille]] and [[bassoon]]). There is also a [[basso continuo]] (separate [[violone]] and organ parts are provided) which underlies both choirs.<ref name=\"bachchoir\">{{Cite web |url=https://bach.org/education/motet-bwv-226/ |title=Motet BWV 226 |website=Bach Choir of Bethlehem |access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref>\nAn accompaniment is also specified for ''Lobet den Herrn''.<ref name=\"Leavis\">{{cite web | url= https://www.jstor.org/stable/731829| title=Bach's Setting of Psalm CXVII (BWV.230) | publisher=OUP | work=[[Music & Letters]]. Vol. 52, No. 1 | date=January 1971 | author=Leavis, Ralph}}  Accessed via JSTOR (subscription required)</ref>\n\n[[La Petite Bande]], for example, uses the orchestration of ''Der Geist hilft unser Schwachheit auf'' for the other pieces for double choir.\nHowever ''a capella'' is long-established tradition,<ref name=\"MT\">Emery, W. (1974). Bach in Practice. [[The Musical Times]], 115(1578), 661-661. doi:10.2307/960490. Accessed via JSTOR (subscription required)</ref> which is also reflected in recordings. The Hilliard Ensemble's OVPP version is mainly ''a capella''. They omit the instrumental parts of ''Der Geist hilft unser Schwachheit auf'', but sing ''Lobet den Herrn'' to organ accompaniment.<ref name=\"Guardian\"/>\n\n== History ==\nThe first of the motets to be recorded was [[Jesu, meine Freude, BWV 227|''Jesu meine Freude'']] in 1927. This version was sung in English.<ref name=\"Bach Cantatas1\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.bach-cantatas.com/Vocal/BWV225-231-Rec1.htm|title= Motets / Recordings \u2013 Part 1 |website=Bach Cantatas Website}}</ref>\n\n== Awards ==\nIn 2010, Suzuki and his ensemble were given a French award ([[Diapason d'Or|Diapason d\u2019Or de l\u2019Ann\u00e9e]]) and a German award ([[Preis der deutschen Schallplattenkritik]]) for their recording of Bach motets on BIS.\n \nJohn Eliot Gardiner, who has won more [[Gramophone Classical Music Awards|Gramophone Awards]] than any other living artist, received one for his second recording of the motets with the Monteverdi Choir on SDG. It was one of the [[Gramophone_Classical_Music_Awards#2013|2013 awards]], the category being \"Baroque Vocal\".\n\nGrete Pedersen with the Norwegian choir [[Det Norske Solistkor]] won a Diapason d'Or in 2018 for their recording of the motets on BIS.\n\n== Discography ==\nThe intention has been to feature versions which are still available. The year given is that of recording. In the case of pre-1980s recordings, the date of reissue on CD can be significantly later than the original recording.\n{{Cantata discography header |work= Bach Motets |show_more=yes |more = Additional info}}\n{{Cantata discography row\n| id = Ramin\n| title = 6 Motetten<ref name=\"Bach Cantatas2\"/>\n| conductor = {{sortname|G\u00fcnther|Ramin}}\n| choir = [[Thomanerchor]]\n| instrumentalists =\n| soloists = {{plainlist|\n}}\n| label = [[Archiv]] (reissue)\n| year = 1950s\n| more =\n}}\n{{Cantata discography row\n| id = Christophers\n| title = The Six Motets<ref name=\"BachCantatas5\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.bach-cantatas.com/Vocal/BWV225-231-Rec5.htm|title= Motets / Recordings \u2013 Part 5 |website=Bach Cantatas Website}}</ref>\n| conductor = {{sortname|Harry|Christophers}}\n| choir = [[The Sixteen]]\n| instrumentalists =\n| soloists = {{plainlist|\n}}\n| label = [[Hyperion Records|Hyperion]]\n| year = 1989\n| more =\n}}\n{{Cantata discography row\n| id = \n| title = Bach Motetten\n| conductor = \n| choir = [[Hilliard Ensemble]]\n| instrumentalists =\n| soloists = {{plainlist|\n}}\n| label = [[ECM Records|ECM]]\n| year = 2003\n| more = second Hilliard recording\n}}\n{{Cantata discography row\n| id = Higginbottom\n| title = Bach Motets<ref name=\"BachCantatas7\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.bach-cantatas.com/Vocal/BWV225-231-Rec7.htm|title= Motets / Recordings \u2013 Part 7 |website=Bach Cantatas Website}}</ref>\n| conductor = [[Edward Higginbottom]]\n| choir = [[Choir of New College, Oxford]]\n| instrumentalists = organ\n| soloists = {{plainlist|\n}}\n| label = Novum<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.newcollegechoir.com/news/?pid=7&nid=1&storyid=12 |title=Recordings |website=Choir of New College, Oxford}}</ref>\n| year = 2008\n| more = organ accompaniment\n}}\n{{Cantata discography row\n| id = Suzuki\n| title = Bach Motets<ref name=\"BIS\"></ref>\n| conductor = {{sortname|Masaaki|Suzuki}}\n| choir = [[Bach Collegium Japan]]\n| instrumentalists =\n| soloists = {{plainlist|\n}}\n| label = [[BIS Records|BIS]]\n| year = 2009\n| more =\n}}\n{{Cantata discography row\n| id = Gardiner2\n| title =Bach Motets<ref name=\"muzie\"></ref>\n| conductor = {{sortname|John Eliot|Gardiner}}\n| choir = [[Monteverdi Choir]]\n| instrumentalists =\n| soloists = {{plainlist|\n}}\n| label = [[Soli Deo Gloria (record label)|SDG]]\n| year = 2011\n| more = second Gardiner recording\n}}\n{{Cantata discography row\n| id = Pedersen\n| title =\n| conductor = {{sortname|Grete|Pedersen}}\n| choir = [[Det Norske Solistkor|Norwegian Soloists' Choir]]\n| instrumentalists = Ensemble Allegria\n| soloists = {{plainlist|\n}}\n| label = BIS\n| year = 2017\n| more = \n}}\n{{End}}\